Text.Value: Little enough. What about him?
As you should. But your father can be beaten, with the right people at your side.
I'm not sure what this has to do with our fight against the cult.
What we found was the first dark seed of this plot - a circle of cultists, with mind flayers in their midst.
That depends entirely on the quality of bard you listen to.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry aside, vaguely amused before moving back onto serious topics

Text.Value: Am I too sentimental for you? Minsc is a warrior from the Time of Troubles - but more than that, he is an old friend.

EditorData.NodeContext: We're being curt with her, but she takes it in stride

Text.Value: As it happens, everything. He was with me the night I first heard that name, connected to some cult gathering in the Undercity.
Minsc fought against Bhaal with you... And I fear Bhaal dearly.
Minsc? Name doesn't ring a bell - but that isn't saying much, given it's me.
It seems that events at Danthelon's have overtaken us. My contact there just sent word - the Harpers have been fractured. Infiltrated by doppelgangers.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: I might need to revisit the flags here - for now the conceit is that if you've spoken to Ninefingers, but the Doppels in DDA are still alive, it'll be assuming DDA has been slaughtered.

Text.Value: I suspect there's more to the story than that.
Perhaps we might have done something to help - or just fallen into the trap along with them. I have only myself to blame.
And I was so busy telling you not to take her bait that I scarcely felt the hook in my own mouth.
Not quite how the ballads describe him, but I suppose there's a certain charm to your version.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry amusement

Text.Value: As simply as that? For no other reason than that I asked?

EditorData.NodeContext: A little taken aback at how quickly we agreed to help her.

EditorData.logicalname: Leads to Nine-Fingers Keene (path where we already know about her)

Text.Value: And you still turned out as well as you did? Amazing.

EditorData.NodeContext: She loves Minsc, just being a little wry and Jaheira-ish

Text.Value: So you left him?
It sounds like he got what he deserved.
So don't be sorry, because I mean to use you if you're willing.
Infection. Indoctrination. Eradication. That has been the fate of everyone the cult has captured so far.

EditorData.NodeContext: Baldly stating the threat - facts, not emotion

Text.Value: It was chaos. He was overrun, dragged down beneath a mass of tentacles.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not a fond rememberance

Text.Value: If I was any kind of friend, I'd have loosed an arrow myself. Or so I thought - until I met you.
Geraldus was the last true Harper in the city we could trust - and that availed him little.

EditorData.NodeContext: Quick, quiet moment of bitterness - she caused his death, but we still have work to do.

Text.Value: Tell me - what do you know of a man named Minsc of Rashemen?

EditorData.NodeContext: Name should spark recognition from fans - an old adventuring companion of hers from previous games.

Text.Value: I'm not asking for promises. Just the chance.

EditorData.NodeContext: Pragmatic

Text.Value: Minsc fought with you against Bhaal before - perhaps he can help me.
What happened?
*Ah, Minsc. A legendary hero who made his home in Baldur's Gate. You're fortunate not to have encountered the madman and his pet hamster during your nocturnal hunts.*
*A legendary warrior of this world - you know his name from histories of the Time of Troubles, a century past.*
*Minsc's is a name you've come across more than once in your studies. A fabled hero from the Time of Troubles, immortalised by books and bards alike.*
*A hero of Baldur's Gate who fought alongside Jaheira during the Time of Troubles. Minsc is a legend.*
*A hero of Baldur's Gate who fought alongside Jaheira during the Time of Troubles. Minsc is a legend.*
*Minsc! You know the legends of the hero who fought alongside Jaheira during the Time of Troubles, alongside his miniature giant space hamster Boo.*
*Minsc. The mad ranger who fought alongside Jaheira during the Time of Troubles. A hero of Baldur's Gate - a hated enemy of your people.*
*Your ruined brain lurches, and bilious intestines squirm. A hero. An enemy most foul.*
*A warrior of this world, his name raised alongside Jaheira's own. Together, they helped end the Time of Troubles a century past.*
*The name is as familiar as Jaheira's own - a hero of the Time of Troubles who saved the city more than once.*
Is this really more important than stopping the Chosen?
And here you are. You made the right choice - don't second-guess yourself.
...perhaps you two will get along.

EditorData.NodeContext: Understated and wry - she's touched that we'd agree so readily, but dryly wondering if that makes us as stupid as Minsc

Text.Value: A... shame of mine. Redoubled, because I did not tell you everything sooner.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not self-pitying - bluntly stating that she blundered, and it cost us - but already moving on. The time for mourning is later.

Text.Value: You'll find he can do little to help there. Too much in the habit of blocking enemy blows with his skull.
I know a little, but it's hard to separate the fact from the fiction.
If he's lucky, they killed him then and there.
Street wailers spin stories from the Time of Troubles, and they save the strangest ones for Minsc. It happens that in his case, most of them are true.
Why are you only telling me this now?
He travelled with you back in the old days.
The world takes much from those who presume to defend it. But, sometimes... you get to take it back.

EditorData.NodeContext: She's been telling the tale rather coldly, but a little bit of fire in that last phrase

Text.Value: You need not preach the cause to me - I've already told you what I sacrificed in its name.

EditorData.NodeContext: Back to being blunt and pragmatic - she's made an emotional appeal to us, but she'll back it up with reason too

Text.Value: And the last time I saw him, I left him to die.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bluntly stated

Text.Value: Perhaps. He's not the first one lost to the cult, and unlikely to be the last.
I'll have a better idea of what that is once we're through the gates. It seems I need to reacquaint myself with this damned city.
Just get to the point.
I have not been overly-generous with the truth. I came here to learn of the Chosen, true enough. But I set my Harpers searching for someone else, too.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bracing herself to tell us everything

Text.Value: I sense you mean no insult, calling scarce a century ago 'the old days'. Which is considerably more insulting.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry aside, vaguely amused before moving back onto serious topics

Text.Value: There isn't a Baldurian alive who doesn't know that name.
Or a stalwart friend to one - that depends entirely on the Bhaalspawn.
Should I know the name?
But few know of his fate, I think. I had hoped to keep it that way.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sigh of regret

Text.Value: We're isolated. This is exactly what Orin wanted.
And would again.

EditorData.NodeContext: No anger. She did what she had to, even if she doesn't like it

Text.Value: A warrior of your people. Formidable, by all counts - I'd relish crossing blades with him.
So what next?
Ah, the empty head. The less forgiving bards might say you two have that in common.
Larger than the legend, I assure you. Twice as loud, too.

EditorData.NodeContext: Amused rememberance - her friend is exactly what the legends say

Text.Value: If I seem suddenly flush with hope and soft feeling, you have only yourself to blame.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry, a little sarcastic - but not harsh. She's genuinely grateful to us

Text.Value: Minsc is an old friend - perhaps my oldest. We fought at one another's backs times beyond counting.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stating plainly - teeing up to say that she left him to die

Text.Value: I'm sorry, Jaheira. That's a cruel choice to have to make.
Orin targeted your Harpers for a reason. What was it?
Except Geraldus - but you cast him aside.
Then let's find him.
How could I not know of the great ranger? He's a hero among heroes.
Minsc the mad Rashemaar - a legendary warrior, no?
Minsc the mad Rashemaar? He's a legend.
But only a fool would discard a potential ally like Minsc. He has faced god and illithid both, just as I have.

EditorData.NodeContext: Back to being blunt and pragmatic - she's made an emotional appeal to us, but she'll back it up with reason too

Text.Value: Whatever blow to the head has addled your thoughts, take comfort - you and Minsc have that in common.
I grew up on childhood tales of the Beloved Ranger.
The point is moot without a means to find him. Without the Harpers, we shall have to find another path...

EditorData.NodeContext: Sigh and back to business - she needs to find a lead.

Text.Value: I had a choice: stay, and let word of this cult die with us. Or leave him, and live to fight another day.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not looking for our approval or condemnation - just stating the facts

Text.Value: Big, bald keeper of vermin, if I recall.

EditorData.logicalname: LOGIC - Leads to "Nine Fingers Keene." in main dialog

Text.Value: Because I was playing the pragmatist, and writing my friend off for dead. Then I met you.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining why she didn't ask for our help before. She's only now acknowleding that she needs it.

Text.Value: Perhaps. He's one of the few people alive who has faced your father before.
Except Geraldus.
We can try, Jaheira. But we don't even know if he's still alive.
A kindness, I hope. My missteps have cost enough lives.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not self-pitying - bluntly stating that she blundered, and it cost us - but already moving on. The time for mourning is later.

Text.Value: Ah! Oh my gods. Minsc!

EditorData.NodeContext: Initial 'Ah!' is meant to be a gasp of excitement (doesn't need to be 'ah,' can be a breathier gasp. This is just for FaceFX). Think a tween talking about harry styles.Kind of talking to the player rather than to Jaheira. Karlach is still trying to play it cool around Jaheira, but she usually fails cause shes' such a fangirl.

Text.Value: My mind is muddled, as you know, but that name sparks something.
Why am I not surprised that young Wyll was well-fed on folk-tales?

EditorData.NodeContext: Amusement, imagining Wyll / the Blade of Frontiers as an innocent child listening to fanciful stories

Text.Value: Until we know who the false-facers are, we cannot trust anyone beyond ourselves.
Except Geraldus. It has been some time since anyone dared rap my knuckles like you did. No less than I deserve.

EditorData.NodeContext: Appraising us - we spoke up against her when no one else dared, and we were right to

Text.Value: But it has not been yours - with your help, perhaps it need not be Minsc's, either.

EditorData.NodeContext: A bald request. No begging or flattery - just asking.

Text.Value: A good question - I don't have an answer, yet, so let me offer an apology instead.
We might have ended it there, cut off at the root. But before I could send for help, Minsc charged in alone.
Who is this Rashemaar you had your Harpers searching for?
*Despite her expectant gaze, the name means nothing to you.*
Do you know - I fear he would be just as happy to meet you.
Before we ever heard of this Absolute, we received word of a gathering in the Undercity.

EditorData.NodeContext: Telling us the tale

Text.Value: Orin knows the hunt. In one stroke, she places the Harpers beyond our reach - separates us from our pack.

EditorData.NodeContext: Angered, little bitter laugh - she's been neatly out-maneuvered

Text.Value: A sworn hunter of Bhaalspawn.
There always is - but that is still the fundamental fact of it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Blunt, not willing to let herself off the hook.

Synopsis: Jaheira's default dialogue. Topics range from her past life to her current goals as they develop. Unless otherwise stated, her tone is confident and to the point. She's a seasoned adventurer with a sardonic sense of humour - and a little less cynical than she might present herself to be.
